&gt; Please consider going through React&#39;s Component lifecycle one more time [here][1]. 

This is what&#39;s happening in your code:

 1. Your component state is initialized to empty object. 
 2. Component&#39;s &lt;code&gt; render() &lt;/code&gt; method is called (where you don&#39;t have the data you need).
 3. Lifecycle method &lt;code&gt;componentDidMount()&lt;/code&gt; is called after initial &lt;code&gt;render()&lt;/code&gt;, where you make an API call and update the state with response data.

**One way to solve this -**

 1. You can consider having a flag `isFetching` in your state which is set to `true` initially. 

```js
state = { isFetching: true };
```

 2. Update your `render()` method to display a fallback UI until your API call is successful i.e. `isFetching` is false;

```js
...

render() {
   const { isFetching } = this.state;
   if (isFetching) {
       return &lt;span&gt; Fetching data &lt;/span&gt;;
   }
   
   console.log(this.state.SiteRep.DV)

   return &lt;p&gt;TEXT&lt;/p&gt;
}
...
```

 3. Add changes to update your `isFetching` flag when API call is being made:

```js
...
componentDidMount() {
       // You&#39;re going to call the API now, set isFetching to true
      this.setState({ isFetching: true });

      const url = &#39;http://datapoint.metoffice.gov.uk/public/data/val/wxfcs/all/json/APIKEY&#39;

      fetch(url)
        .then(response =&gt; {return response.json()})
        .then(data =&gt; {
          // API call done, set data and make isFetching false.
          this.setState({ data, isFetching: false });
        })      
    }
...

```

**Another approach** would be to add the initial state such as:

```js

state = {
    SiteRep: {
      DV: {}
    }
}
```
&gt; With this approach, initially you would see no data but once API response is updated in your component state, component will re-render. 

Personally I&#39;d take the first approach as you can have finer control over your `render()`

  [1]: https://reactjs.org/docs/react-component.html#the-component-lifecycle

